page.title: 13LANDSCAPE IN SELSEY
page.content: Two thirds of this flat peninsula is farmland with few houses.The estuary in the northeast is surrounded by marshland and mudflats.The southern third of this area is densely populated with caravans and a variety of types of building.East Beach is a steeply sloping,flint pebble beach which at low tide reveals to the north the gravel Winkle Beds.It is divided by groynes at regular intervals to prevent the removal of the pebbles and there is a sea wall that was built 1959_1960.West Beach is a shingle and sand beach less steep than East Beach.There are signs of erosion on the raised beach cliff.A variety of fossils can be found on the beaches around Selsey,including sharks' teeth,turritella ,cardita and other fossils dating back 50 million years.
